There is power in that frame — but also a useful tension.

We are not infinitely unconstrained. Reality gives us starting conditions: genetics, history, responsibilities, limits, circumstances, time. Those are part of the terrain.

But within that terrain, humans do something extraordinary: we reinterpret, practice, adapt, choose, build, and become. Identity is not only inheritance; it is also authorship.

A seed is not “anything.” An oak seed does not become a whale.

But an oak seed can become a sapling, a shelter, a forest, a ship’s timber, a thousand futures hidden inside one beginning.

Or in your cadence:

We are not only what we are told we are.
We are also what we repeatedly choose, build, and refuse to surrender becoming.